<div class="lb-section-row region-body"><div class="lb-region lb-region--main"><div class="block block-layout-builder block-inline-blockrecommend-stories"><h2>Recommended Stories</h2><div class="teaser-grid"><article class="node node--type-story node--view-mode-card"><div class="node__content"><a href="/stories/justice-all" ref="bookmark"><div class="field field--name-field-header-image field--type-entity-reference field--label-hidden field__item"><figure class="media media--type-image media--view-mode--50-width"><img src="/sites/default/files/styles/50_percent/public/2024-02/UNI509406.jpg?itok=hKfdWGbc" width="458" height="305" alt="Nabintu, 12, attends class at Lwashi Primary School in Lushagala, North Kivu, DR Congo, on Jan. 19, 2024." loading="lazy" class="image-style-_0-percent" /></figure></div><h2><span class="field field--name-title field--type-string field--label-hidden">Justice for All</span></h2><div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><p>UNICEF and partners are committed to championing the rights of every child and advocating for equity and justice for all.</p></div></a></div></article><article class="node node--type-story node--view-mode-card"><div class="node__content"><a href="/stories/girls-rights-are-human-rights-fight-end-child-marriage" ref="bookmark"><div class="field field--name-field-header-image field--type-entity-reference field--label-hidden field__item"><figure class="media media--type-image media--view-mode--50-width"><img src="/sites/default/files/styles/50_percent/public/2024-01/XXXScreenshot%202023-12-28%20at%202.02.18%20PM.png?itok=ryBQzobY" width="458" height="304" alt="On Sept. 21, 2023, in Monapo District, Nampula Province, Mozambique, girls and boys participated in UNICEF-supported activities designed to encourage young people to avoid early marriage. " loading="lazy" class="image-style-_0-percent" /></figure></div><h2><span class="field field--name-title field--type-string field--label-hidden">Girls&#039; Rights Are Human Rights: <strong>The Fight to End Child Marriage</strong></span></h2><div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><p>UNICEF and Zonta International are tackling established practices and bolstering local systems to secure girls’ human rights.</p></div></a></div></article><article class="node node--type-story node--view-mode-card"><div class="node__content"><a href="/stories/kind-fund-desks-help-students-learn-malawi" ref="bookmark"><div class="field field--name-field-header-image field--type-entity-reference field--label-hidden field__item"><figure class="media media--type-image media--view-mode--50-width"><img src="/sites/default/files/styles/50_percent/public/2023-11/IMG_8535.JPGDesks.JPG?itok=VHwCE_Vk" width="458" height="305" alt="Students sit at their desks, provided by the K.I.N.D. Fund, at Kalima Primary School in Malawi in October 2023.." loading="lazy" class="image-style-_0-percent" /></figure></div><h2><span class="field field--name-title field--type-string field--label-hidden">K.I.N.D. Fund Desks <strong>Help Students Learn in Malawi</strong></span></h2><div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><p>The K.I.N.D. (Kids in Need of Desks) Fund, a longstanding partnership between UNICEF and MSNBC, is bringing quality education to students in Malawi.</p></div></a></div></article><article class="node node--type-story node--view-mode-card"><div class="node__content"><a href="/stories/solar-powered-water-systems-game-changer-girls-rwanda" ref="bookmark"><div class="field field--name-field-header-image field--type-entity-reference field--label-hidden field__item"><figure class="media media--type-image media--view-mode--50-width"><img src="/sites/default/files/styles/50_percent/public/2023-08/UNI414404%20%281%29.jpg.960w.jpg?itok=z_k903cY" width="458" height="309" alt="UNICEF Goodwill Ambasador Vanessa Nakate walks with (from left) Bonette, Graciella and Adele in Kigarama Sector, Kirehe District, Eastern Province of Rwanda. " loading="lazy" class="image-style-_0-percent" /></figure></div><h2><span class="field field--name-title field--type-string field--label-hidden"><strong>Solar-Powered Water Systems a Game Changer</strong> for Girls in Rwanda</span></h2><div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><p>Sustainable solar-powered water systems save money, protect communities from climate shocks and ease the water burden for girls.</p></div></a></div></article><article class="node node--type-story node--view-mode-card"><div class="node__content"><a href="/stories/redemption-and-resilience-keeping-rohingya-refugee-girls-school" ref="bookmark"><div class="field field--name-field-header-image field--type-entity-reference field--label-hidden field__item"><figure class="media media--type-image media--view-mode--50-width"><img src="/sites/default/files/styles/50_percent/public/2023-07/3.%20Roshida%20with%20her%20grandmother%28Photo%20Credit%20by%20Taharul%20Islam%29.jpeg?itok=WpNVZ8zf" width="458" height="312" alt="Rohingya refugees Roshida, right, and her grandmother in Cox&#039;s Bazar, Bangladesh." loading="lazy" class="image-style-_0-percent" /></figure></div><h2><span class="field field--name-title field--type-string field--label-hidden">Redemption and Resilience: Keeping <strong>Rohingya Refugee Girls</strong> in School  </span></h2><div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><p>Meet Roshida, a Rohingya orphan who narrowly escaped child marriage to find new hope through education in Bangladesh.</p></div></a></div></article><article class="node node--type-story node--view-mode-card"><div class="node__content"><a href="/stories/green-girls-eco-charcoal-project-takes-burundi" ref="bookmark"><div class="field field--name-field-header-image field--type-entity-reference field--label-hidden field__item"><figure class="media media--type-image media--view-mode--50-width"><img src="/sites/default/files/styles/50_percent/public/2023-07/UNI405254.mp4_.00_03_47_22.Still004.jpg.STOVEPIPE.960e.jpg?itok=Z9vbQpt4" width="458" height="258" alt="In Burundi, UNICEF&#039;s Green Girls 2.0 initiative trains girls and women to source and manufacture eco-friendly charcoal." loading="lazy" class="image-style-_0-percent" /></figure></div><h2><span class="field field--name-title field--type-string field--label-hidden">Green Girls Eco-Charcoal Project Takes Off in <strong>Burundi</strong></span></h2><div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><p>UNICEF Burundi's Green Girls eco-charcoal initiative doesn't just prevent deforestation; it also drives equity and local business development. [VIDEO]</p></div></a></div></article></div><a href="/stories?issues=11518" class="btn btn-primary">See all</a></div></div></div> </section>
